Fig. 8
 presented the adsorption-photocatalytic removal of CIP by the samples. All dispersions were kept stirring for 60 min in dark to get adsorption-desorption equilibrium. The equilibrium adsorption capacity showed that the introduction of rGO promoted the adsorption of pollutant (Fig. 8a), which was consistent with the results discussed above. Under visible light irradiation, the photocatalytic degradation was triggered. The photocatalytic activity of BiOCl/CQDs was higher than that of BiOCl after incorporating CQDs. Moreover, the photocatalytic activity was further enhanced by introducing rGO. In Fig. 8b, the corresponding kinetic fitting curves showed that the photocatalytic activities of BiOCl/CQDs/rGO-x were improved with the content of rGO increasing from 5% to 10 %, but further increase in rGO content led to decrease in photocatalytic activities, owing to the shading effect of rGO [53]. The photocatalytic performance of BiOCl/CQDs/rGO-10 was the highest and the degradation rate constant (0.0146 min−1) was 3.8 times and 10.4 times larger than those of BiOCl/CQDs (0.0038 min−1) and BiOCl (0.0014 min−1). Therefore, the CIP removal efficiency of BiOCl/CQDs/rGO-10 reached up to 87 % (Fig. 8a), which was ascribed to the excellent adsorption ability due to the introduction of rGO and improved photocatalytic activity due to the co-introduction of CQDs and rGO. Compared with reported photocatalysts, BiOCl/CQDs/rGO-10 in this work did possess good adsorption-photocatalytic performance towards CIP under visible light (Table 1
).

To gain deep understanding of photocatalytic mechanism, the relative band positions of BiOCl were determined. The band gap of BiOCl was calculated to be 3.35 eV from the Tauc plot (Fig. 6). In addition, the EVB (valence band potential) and ECB (conduction band potential) of BiOCl were calculated to be 3.52 eV and 0.17 eV by Mulliken electronegativity theory (EVB = X – Ec + 0.5Eg
                         and ECB = EVB − Eg
                        ) [66]. Interestingly, the photocatalytic degradation results (Fig. 8) indicated that the wide-band-gap BiOCl could be excited by visible light and EPR spectra (Fig. S4) confirmed the presence of oxygen vacancies, in which a characteristic signal of oxygen vacancies at g value of 2.0036 was found.
